article.headline: Central Florida 72, Tulane 51
article.story: ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Josh Peppers led the Golden Knights with 11 points as Central Florida defeated Tulane, 72-51, Saturday in Conference USA play. UCF (10-11, 4-4) made 19-of-22 foul shots and forced 22 Tulane turnovers (9-13, 4-5). The Golden Knights broke a three-game losing skid and also ended Tulane's four-game winning streak with the 21-point victory -- UCF's largest margin of victory in conference play. UCF connected on nine 3-pointers and shot 47.4 percent from downtown while Tulane made just two 3-pointers and shot 18.2 percent from long range. Anthony Williams also finished in the double digits with 10 points for UCF. David Gomez scored a game-high 13 points for Tulane while Quincy Davis chipped in 10 for the Green Wave. UCF took a 34-25 lead into intermission. The Golden Knights got a lift from their bench in the first 20 minutes of play as UCF's reserves outscored Tulane's bench 17-3, including six points from Jermaine Taylor. Tulane committed 14 turnovers in the opening stanza and shot 30 percent from the field, including just 16.7 percent from three-point range. The Golden Knights scored 12 points off those 14 turnovers and shot 62.5 percent from three-point range (5-of-8) in the opening half. Tulane cut the lead to seven in the second half with just over 12 minutes remaining, but the Golden Knights went on an 11-2 run over the next 2:47 to extend the lead to a game-high 18 at 56-38.
